---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Testimonials Data Architecture',
  description:
    'Internal documentation for how testimonials are modeled, stored, and used across The Second Design website via Google Sheets.',
};

const SHEET_URL = 'https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1xHTYHuGVZx6U4DwrzRbVZiDdxAbkKYtOJAc6FTA6DO0/edit';
const FORM_URL = 'https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdTh_9Xqdtpzow1Za_2c6tIXXQQfQwoRwycCpVQO2X1uKLucQ/viewform';
const FORM_EDIT_URL = 'https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1xalKAnoYLjDCG9VCUG3FN5Xm8xGm9bVgw4ZbTDarHgs/edit';
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <section class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-slate-50 dark:bg-slate-950">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl mx-auto prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 mb-3">
        Internal docs
      </p>
      <h1>Testimonials Data Architecture</h1>

      <p>
        This page documents how testimonials are modeled, stored, and used across The Second Design website. All data
        lives in a <a href={SHEET_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google Sheet</a> and is fetched
        automatically at build time.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-950/50 border border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800 rounded-lg">
        <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100">
          <strong>Quick links:</strong>
          <a href={SHEET_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="ml-2 underline">Google Sheet</a> ·
          <a href={FORM_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="ml-2 underline">Add Testimonial (Form)</a> ·
          <a href={FORM_EDIT_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="ml-2 underline">Edit Form</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>1. Overview</h2>
      <p>The testimonials system is built on four core entities, each stored in a separate sheet tab:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Products</strong> – offerings like Real World Ready, FOSS Hack 2025, consulting, or online courses.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Partners</strong> – organisations like TinkerHub, FOSS United, Edison, Maven, or Udemy.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Persons</strong> – named individuals who give testimonials (students, clients, collaborators).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Testimonials</strong> – the actual feedback: quotes, videos, emails, screenshots, tweets, etc.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>A single testimonial can:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Optionally link to a person (or be anonymous).</li>
        <li>Link to one or more products.</li>
        <li>Link to one or more partners.</li>
        <li>Be scoped to a specific product or to the overall brand.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2. Data flow</h2>
      <p>Here's how data moves from Google Sheets to the live website:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Input</strong> – Add testimonials via the Google Form (linked to the sheet), or edit data directly in
          the Google Sheet tabs (Products, Partners, Persons, Form Responses 1).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deploy</strong> – Click "Website → Deploy to Live Site" in the Google Sheet menu, OR push to the main
          branch on GitHub.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Fetch</strong> – During the Netlify build, the <code>prebuild</code> script runs{' '}
          <code>scripts/fetch-testimonials.js</code> which reads all four sheet tabs and writes JSON files to{' '}
          <code>src/data/</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Build</strong> – Astro builds the site, reading the JSON files via <code>testimonials.ts</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Live</strong> – The updated site goes live on Netlify.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>3. Sheet structure</h2>
      <p>
        The Google Sheet has four tabs. The column names in row 1 of each tab must match exactly (case-sensitive):
      </p>

      <h3>3.1 Products tab</h3>
      <table class="text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Column</th>
            <th>Description</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>product_id</td><td>Unique ID, lowercase with dashes (e.g., <code>rwr-foss2025</code>)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>name</td><td>Main product name (e.g., "Real World Ready")</td></tr>
          <tr><td>category</td><td>Bucket: real_world_ready, consulting, online_course_design, generic</td></tr>
          <tr><td>variant_name</td><td>Optional variant label (e.g., "FOSS Hack 2025")</td></tr>
          <tr><td>partner_ids</td><td>Comma-separated partner IDs</td></tr>
          <tr><td>platform</td><td>Where it runs: On-site, Maven, Udemy, or blank</td></tr>
          <tr><td>url</td><td>Landing page URL</td></tr>
          <tr><td>description_short</td><td>One-liner for UI</td></tr>
          <tr><td>status</td><td>Usually "active"</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>3.2 Partners tab</h3>
      <table class="text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Column</th>
            <th>Description</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>partner_id</td><td>Unique ID, lowercase with dashes (e.g., <code>foss-united</code>)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>name</td><td>Official organisation name</td></tr>
          <tr><td>relationship_type</td><td>community, client, platform, employer</td></tr>
          <tr><td>logo_url</td><td>Optional logo path</td></tr>
          <tr><td>website_url</td><td>Organisation website</td></tr>
          <tr><td>description_short</td><td>One-line description</td></tr>
          <tr><td>priority</td><td>Lower numbers appear first</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>3.3 Persons tab</h3>
      <table class="text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Column</th>
            <th>Description</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>person_id</td><td>Unique ID, lowercase with dashes (e.g., <code>sai-rahul</code>)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>name</td><td>Full name</td></tr>
          <tr><td>designation</td><td>Title or role</td></tr>
          <tr><td>company</td><td>Organisation name</td></tr>
          <tr><td>partner_id</td><td>Link to partner if applicable</td></tr>
          <tr><td>linkedin_url</td><td>LinkedIn profile URL</td></tr>
          <tr><td>other_link</td><td>Personal site or article</td></tr>
          <tr><td>headshot_url</td><td>Portrait image path</td></tr>
          <tr><td>relationship_type</td><td>student, client, partner_staff, collaborator, participant</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>3.4 Form Responses 1 tab (Testimonials)</h3>
      <p>
        This tab contains all testimonial data. Key columns:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Select Person</strong> – dropdown to pick existing person or "Add New Person"</li>
        <li><strong>New Person fields</strong> – name, designation, company, LinkedIn (for new people)</li>
        <li><strong>Product</strong> – dropdown of products</li>
        <li><strong>Partner</strong> – dropdown of partners</li>
        <li><strong>Scope</strong> – product or brand</li>
        <li><strong>Audience Type</strong> – student, client, partner, collaborator</li>
        <li><strong>Source Type</strong> – text, video, image, email, blog, tweet</li>
        <li><strong>Quote (Short)</strong> – 1-2 punchy lines for cards</li>
        <li><strong>Quote (Long)</strong> – full context</li>
        <li><strong>Rating</strong> – numeric rating if applicable</li>
        <li><strong>Language</strong> – en, ml, etc.</li>
        <li><strong>Testimonial Date</strong> – when the testimonial was given</li>
        <li><strong>Priority</strong> – hero, high, normal, low</li>
        <li><strong>Publish Immediately?</strong> – Yes/No</li>
        <li><strong>Internal Notes</strong> – never shown on site</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>4. How to add a testimonial</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Option A: Use the Google Form</strong> (easiest)
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Open the <a href={FORM_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Testimonials Form</a>.</li>
        <li>Fill in the fields — dropdowns for persons, products, and partners make it easy.</li>
        <li>Submit the form.</li>
        <li>Open the <a href={SHEET_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google Sheet</a>, review the new row, and set "Publish Immediately?" to Yes.</li>
        <li>Click "Website → Deploy to Live Site" in the menu bar.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        <strong>Option B: Edit the sheet directly</strong>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Open the <a href={SHEET_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google Sheet</a> and go to the "Form Responses 1" tab.</li>
        <li>Add a new row at the bottom with testimonial details.</li>
        <li>Set "Publish Immediately?" to Yes when ready to go live.</li>
        <li>Click "Website → Deploy to Live Site" in the menu bar.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>5. How to add products, partners, or persons</h2>
      <p>Edit the respective sheet tab directly:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Go to the Products, Partners, or Persons tab.</li>
        <li>Add a new row at the bottom with all required fields.</li>
        <li>Use lowercase-with-dashes for all IDs.</li>
        <li>Deploy to make the new entity available on the site.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        New products, partners, and persons will automatically appear in the Google Form dropdowns after you refresh
        the form.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Display rules</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          The homepage shows testimonials with <code>scope: brand</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Product pages show testimonials with <code>scope: product</code> filtered by product_id.
        </li>
        <li>
          Testimonials are sorted by priority (hero → high → normal → low) then by date (newest first).
        </li>
        <li>
          Only testimonials with <code>is_published: true</code> appear on the site.
        </li>
        <li>
          Videos and blogs show watch/read links. Screenshots display the image.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>7. Technical details</h2>
      <p>For developers:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <code>scripts/fetch-testimonials.js</code> – fetches all sheet tabs via the public gviz API (no auth
          required, sheet must be "published to web").
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>src/data/testimonials.ts</code> – helper that loads JSON and resolves references between entities.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>package.json</code> has <code>"prebuild": "node scripts/fetch-testimonials.js"</code> so data is
          always fresh on deploy.
        </li>
        <li>
          The deploy trigger in Google Apps Script calls the Netlify build hook via POST request.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-950/50 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-lg">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 dark:text-amber-100">
          <strong>Important:</strong> The Google Sheet must be "Published to web" (File → Share → Publish to web) for
          the fetch script to work. Only publish the specific tabs needed, not the entire document with edit access.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
